Step 3: Factor the quadratic equation to find the values of \(a\). In this case, the equation factors nicely.
\begin{align*}
(2a + 1)(3a + 1) &= 0
\end{align*}

Step 4: Apply the zero-product property which states that if a product of factors equals zero, at least one of the factors must equal zero.
\begin{align*}
2a + 1 = 0 &\quad \text{or} \quad 3a + 1 = 0
\end{align*}

Step 5: Solve each equation for \(a\) to find the possible values of \(a\).
\begin{align*}
a &= -\frac{1}{2} \quad \text{or} \quad a = -\frac{1}{3}
\end{align*}

