&= c
\end{align*}

Step 2: Find the value of $f(1)$, by substituting $x=1$ into the quadratic equation $f(x) = ax^2 + bx + c$:
\begin{align*}
f(1) &= a(1)^2 + b(1) + c \\
&= a + b + c
\end{align*}

Step 3: Express $a + b + 2c$ in terms of $f(0)$ and $f(1)$:
\begin{align*}
a + b + 2c &= c + (a + b + c) \\
&= f(0) + f(1)
\end{align*}

Step 4: Use the graph to identify the points through which the graph $y = f(x)$ passes. Specifically, identify the coordinates of $f(0)$ and $f(1)$. The graph passes through the points $(0,7)$ and $(1,4)$, giving us $f(0) = 7$ and $f(1) = 4$.

Step 5: Calculate $a+b+2c$ using the values found for $f(0)$ and $f(1)$:
\begin{align*}
a + b + 2c &= f(0) + f(1) \\
&= 7 + 4 \\
&= 11
\end{align*}

