answer:
First, we expand the given product using the distributive property:

Step 1: Apply the distributive property to the first term in the first parenthesis:
\begin{align*}
(3x+2y+1)(x+4y+5) &= 3x \cdot (x+4y+5) + \text{... (other terms)} \\
&= 3x^2 + 12xy + 15x + \text{... (other terms)}
\end{align*}

Step 2: Apply the distributive property to the second term in the first parenthesis:
\begin{align*}
&= \text{... (previous terms)} + 2y \cdot (x+4y+5) + \text{... (other term)} \\
&= \text{... (previous terms)} + 2xy + 8y^2 + 10y + \text{... (other term)}
\end{align*}

Step 3: Apply the distributive property to the third term in the first parenthesis:
\begin{align*}
&= \text{... (previous terms)} + 1 \cdot (x+4y+5) \\
&= \text{... (previous terms)} + x + 4y + 5
\end{align*}

Step 4: Combine the like terms:
\begin{align*}
&= 3x^2 + (12xy + 2xy) + (15x + x) + 8y^2 + (10y + 4y) + 5 \\
&= 3x^2 + 14xy + 16x + 8y^2 + 14y + 5
\end{align*}

Step 5: Identify the terms containing some power of \( y \): These are \( 14xy \), \( 8y^2 \), and \( 14y \).

Step 6: Sum the coefficients of the identified terms: 
\begin{align*}
14 (coefficient \ of \ 14xy) + 8 (coefficient \ of \ 8y^2) + 14 (coefficient \ of \ 14y) &= 14 + 8 + 14 \\
&= 36
\end{align*}

Final Answer: 36.0

